President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate several individuals for key leadership positions in his administration. 

Firstly, Jennifer M. Adams is nominated for Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Cabo Verde. Adams is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service with the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) and has served in various positions, including USAID Faculty Representative at the National War College and Acting Assistant Administrator, Global Health Bureau at USAID.

Nicole D. Theriot is nominated for Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Co-operative Republic of Guyana. Theriot is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as the Principal Officer in Karachi, Pakistan. She has held various positions within the U.S. Embassy, including Deputy Chief of Mission in Port-au-Prince, Haiti, and Political Counselor in Kabul, Afghanistan.

Joel Matthew Szabat is nominated for Member of the AMTRAK Board of Directors. Szabat is retiring from the US Department of Transportation (DOT) after 38 years of government service. He has held various positions within DOT, including Deputy Assistant Secretary for Aviation & International Affairs and Acting Under Secretary for Policy. Szabat has also served as the Executive Director of the United States Maritime Administration.

Lastly, Robert G. Taub is nominated for Member of the Postal Regulatory Commission. Taub served as Chairman of the Postal Regulatory Commission for over 6 years and has more than 40 years of public service experience. Before joining the Commission, he was a Principal Civilian Advisor to the Secretary of the Army and Chief of Staff to U.S. Representative John M. McHugh.

These nominations highlight the diverse experience and expertise of the individuals chosen to serve in these key leadership roles within the Biden administration.